segments.text: General LeMay arrived at about the Vietnamese situation and their air force, your air bases?
Well, he came in and visited not only our own air bases, which I think we had two at the time, but he went out and visited some of the Vietnamese commands.
And I don't know that we really...

came to any conclusion, you really don't come to any conclusion when you're just following some four-star general around where he has a massive staff with him and he's just looking at the situation, getting appraised of what was going on out there.
Okay, well what were your impressions?
You must have been coming from Hawaii and going to this primitive land.
You must have had some impression about our capabilities of fighting that war.
Well, I would say that your impression was you couldn't really depend on the Vietnamese people to do very much of your fighting for you, unless you took a long time in training them.
and organizing these mountain guard backwoodsmen into the fighting force.
I don't know.
You look at the problem of just communications.
Certainly these old mountain guard people are certainly not going to learn any English, or not very much.
trying to train a foreigner in the English language for him to fight your war.
It was a major problem.
Do you think that was a major problem of American strategy?
Let me answer that.
Do you think that part of the problem of American military was being rather
Gung-ho on the war in Vietnam was, I mean, that we set ourselves up as we can't win this war.
You're talking about all the problems now.
Did the military back in 1962 perceive all these problems, or was it just a can-do type feeling?
No, I think it's a matter of the strategy of just gradually putting another small
I really think the strategy that we had at that time was a small build up to just almost stay even with Yvette Kahn.
It was only much later I think that we even committed
major forces and had we committed those two or three years earlier, we probably would have gotten the job done.
But we were always just committing enough of the force to kind of stay even.
Of course, this is what we're talking about now, Secretary McNamara's idea of flexible response.
Do you remember what your thoughts about flexible response were and what your commander's thoughts about McNamara?
Well, see your problem in the military, your commanders really don't get involved in all the top secret information that you have at the headquarters.
And like the commander Masawa, he's completely out of the picture.
I mean, they don't provide you any information up there.
You have a different mission altogether.
So your commander of your 13th Air Force, who was in the Philippines, who was supporting the Vietnamese war, and then you had a brigadier general at that time, chief of the
military assistance group over in Dunham, so that you don't really have a lot of people coming in and pounding the desk and saying, let's do this and let's do that.
What about at the Pacific Air Force headquarters?
What about there?
Four-star general, he must have had some dealings with that.

uh... secretary of defense well yeah i hear any scuttle about uh... what they thought about well you're uh... you don't you don't uh... i don't think you i don't think you hear general o'donnell uh... pounding his desk and saying mcnamara is crazy i mean you just don't
you don't do that type of thing.
I just don't think that you really criticize your superiors before your juniors.
It's a know-it-all type of thing.
Now, I have met with Michael Mayer when he came out to the PACCOM headquarters and where he gave you a briefing.
his staff would give you a briefing or you'd give him a briefing first as to what the status of activities were.
But you didn't have your commander sitting around pounding and saying that this guy's crazy because he's just not being a good commander.
When you met McNamara, what were your impressions?
He was a whiz kid type of thing, and of course he's the one that set up the program of retiring people over 55.
You weren't too excited about it.
I wasn't too excited about it, no.
And I'm wondering what his ideas on retirement are today.
Certainly it's not the idea that you
that he should be put out to pasture by the time he's fifty-five because he's beyond that age now and I still say he's still working.
He's retiring next year I think, or at the end of this year as the president of the World Bank, but he's way over fifty-five.
Yes, right.
Okay, do you remember, you said that you wrote a report, you and General LeMay, or you had some input on that.
report on the mission, your visit to Vietnam.
Do you remember anything that you said in that report?
No, I really don't.
I was looking through my files where I was searching for my resume and this type of thing.
I ran across a document which covered General LeMay's trip to Vietnam, but I don't remember anything about it.
Was he in pretty good humor to see you again?
Oh yeah, he always remembered me.
Well, I think that we should talk about what you think, after 30 years in the service, are the highlights of your career
and what we might call the low points if we can.
It seems to me like some of the major highlights, a commander of the 39th Air Division, seems like one of the jobs that you enjoyed the most.
And then, of course, when you were the commander of the 379th down in Homestead, sounds like you were very interested then in the 823rd.
Am I right in those assumptions?
Well, I basically like to be boss.
I mean, I'm...
And of course, I think that the jobs that I had in the Air Force were real quality jobs.
I mean, being, well, going, I'd say my first big job was the radio school at Sioux Falls, South Dakota, where you build it from scratch with using a
having available to you a bunch of second lieutenants and you were the lieutenant colonel and the second senior officer on the base, why that job I enjoyed.
I would say the next job I enjoyed was the radar school down in Boca Raton, Florida.
Setting that up.
Ends up setting that up.
I'm not a
I'm not a particularly strong staff guy.
I like to be out, rather than sitting behind a desk writing papers, I like to be out generating enthusiasm in people.
Then from there, commanding the security service was a very challenging job.
You're talking about a low point.
I would say that when I was removed from being commander of security service up to the deputy director of NSA, although the jobs were equivalent, I thought I was being moved out and replaced by
a higher-ranking colonel who at the same time was promoted to BG.
So did you consider that job as the deputy director of the National Security Agency sort of a setback?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, I consider that a setback.
A demotion?
Would you consider it a demotion?
Well, you can't really say a demotion.
As far as I was concerned, it was a demotion.
I mean, it was an equal-status job.
Yeah.
And of course, I was Wade Jr. to General Lynn, or Roy Lynn, who replaced me as Commander of the Security Service.
And he was promoted at the same time he was moved in to a BG-7 grade.
So I figured I'd work my tail off getting the Security Service organized, and then he gets promoted and comes down and take over
a pretty well-run organization.
And you wanted that job.
Well, I was interested in keeping the job.
But you wanted the star and you wanted... Well, I was interested in a job and I was interested in promotion.
Sure.
And so therefore, at that time, I figured that maybe I wasn't going to get promoted.
And because...
Neither one of the deputies were, although they were one star slots, neither one of them had been promoted.
Navy, Army, or the Air Force.
And I'd say that was a low spot anyway.
I was unhappy with the job at being director.
And it was at this time when you were getting your MBA and considering
of getting out of the service.
Yeah, if I didn't move from, I was willing to put up with it for a couple of years.
And then from there.
There you have four command jobs in a row.
Then from there you go to 379th Bomb Wing, which is a very, that job I thoroughly enjoyed.
And being a commander of eight
23rd Air Division was a step up and you got promoted.
Being moved out of that job into a MAG job, I figured that was a demotion.
Although both of them were occupied by a Major General, I mean a Brigadier General.
So I replaced the Brigadier General.
You can't say it was demotion as far as I was concerned.
But it wasn't a command.
Well, it wasn't a command job.
Then of course you moved to the 39th Air Division.
I moved to Sawa.
And again, that was a good job.
And the two jobs that I had in PACAF headquarters were real good jobs.
I mean, I thoroughly enjoyed them.
And because you were almost a deputy commander there in your particular field and you had a lot of responsibility.
What was your favorite job of your entire career?
Well, I would say that your Sioux Falls, South Dakota was a real good job.
I mean I thoroughly enjoyed that.
thoroughly enjoyed, well the one at the radar school was not as enjoyable because I wasn't technically qualified as a radar officer.
I mean I was, you were directing an organization in which you weren't technically qualified to supervise the technical aspects.
You had to depend on somebody else to provide that.
The only thing is you just
just by force that you change the character of the school.
Then from there going to 5th Bomber Command as a communications officer, I'd say that's one of my low spots.
I've gone to B-29 Transition School and then you get shipped all over to
to an organization as a communications officer, and although you were an administrator of a technical radio school, I still wasn't a technical officer as far as communications was concerned.
I couldn't really teach radio, the theory of it.
I was administrator type.
And then I always worked myself out of these communication jobs.
I was very happy with those.
But when you get into being the A3, the operations, deputy for operations in 5th Bomber Command, deputy of operations for 5th Air Force, I like those jobs pretty well.
Although I like being in that command of the 315th.
I was back in my
was a true element.
Because I just liked to be responsible and then the Air Force Security Service would have gone over.
But so, any command job, I was really like to be the boss.
Did, you know, very few men become generals.
Did you consider yourself during your career ambitious?
Well, yeah, I watched everybody else getting promoted.
Every promotion that came out, you looked it over and tried to figure out how he got promoted and you didn't.
And did you think that your advancement was, when you figured these things out or tried to figure these things out, did you think that your advancement in the
in the military was because of luck, or fate, or something that you had no control over, or was it because of your own actions, your own behavior?
Which was most important?
I think your own actions and your own behavior.
I think that had I been in a different position, I would have gotten promoted with or
the guy who did get promoted in that particular job.
I mean, he just happened to get selected for that.
And I know that when I came back from Japan the first time, I was being considered for a job in the Pentagon being the director of technical training.
It was Air Force-wide.
And the guy, the individual, one of my classmates who took that, who got that job, and I kind of went to their war college.
So it just happened that I got selected to war college instead of taking that job.
He and I were probably equally qualified.
Well, he ended up with a four-star, as a four-star general.
It's just one of those, that particular thing, there's no way of guiding your career
into the lucky spots.
My philosophy, I guess, was that if you do a good job, you'll come to the attention of the right people.
Maybe that I didn't pay politics, play enough golf with the boss that he got to know you better personally.
Is that important in the service?
Oh, I think that it's... Well, it's hard to say.
It's not my philosophy of operation.
But you look at some of the people who did get to be known by their golfing and personal contact, they seem to get ahead a little faster than...
the ones who really kept their light under the bushel.
In other words, those people promoted themselves more?
Is that what we're talking about?
Well, they got promoted because they got to be known more.
You have to face the fact.
If a guy works as a major in the Secretary of Defense's office,
or a lieutenant colonel, why then the secretary of defense, if he sends a note down to the chief of the staff of the Air Force to promote this guy, the chances are he's going to get promoted.
I mean, he doesn't have to go through all the selection process.
I think that it's
it's really a problem of getting to be known.
I mean, just like running the radio school at Sioux Falls, you've got to be known.
You've got to be known by the commanders in Second Air Force who were cadres, and your contemporaries are the ones that really promote you, I think.
I don't know, you can't

Normally the setbacks that you have, I think you have to look at them that although your ego gets bruised rather thoroughly, maybe if you look back on it, maybe that's the best thing that happened to you.
Maybe you don't get fired, maybe you get replaced.
And so maybe you change the direction just a little bit in your career.
You've been a success both in the military and in your civilian career in the building business.
And you've had assignments and leadership in both the military and in the civilian.
How do you get ahead in both of these?
Is there any difference between getting ahead in the business world and getting ahead
in the military?
Well, there's one major difference.
In the military, when someone verbally tells you they're going to do something, the chances are they're going to do it.
In the civilian business world, a lot of people tell you they're going to do something, and they have no intention of ever doing it.
I mean, it's a question of honesty here?
It's a matter of honesty, as far as I'm concerned.
You think that officers in the Air Corps in general are more honest than the average businessman?
I would say so, yeah.
I'd say honesty in civilian life is improved by having it in writing.
I mean, it's very simple.
You just can't depend on...
on people to do what they say they're going to do.
Whereas in the military, you've been taught for four years at the military academy and 30 years in the military that a man's word is his bond.
And in civilian life, that's just not true.
You can't pay an individual who says that he's completed your roof without going out and looking at the roof to see that he has completed it.
The chances are he hasn't completed it.
So you just have to check and double check.
And as I mentioned,
Although the executive vice president of a bank told me when I was getting in a small business that this is a real fine, small company.
He had lots of contracts.
And he knew doggone well that wasn't exactly true.
That they were in the red.
Yeah, they were in the red.
And all he was trying to do is protect himself.
And that type of dishonesty
would not happen in the officer ranks.
I don't think so, no.
I don't.
Well, it's probably a different situation because when you're talking to, communicating with officers, you're not dealing with finances.
Sure, not dealing with money.
You're not dealing with money or protection or loss of money.
You're...
you're really talking about efficiency of operations of an outfit or this type of thing.
What about, oh, I don't know, backbiting to get ahead, stabbing another officer in the back so you can get a little leverage on getting that promotion before somebody else?
Is there much of that in the service?
Did you find?
No, I don't.
It's really not evident.
It's really not evident.

Because I think when you're a staff officer of General O'Donnell or you're a staff officer of General Burns, I think you have a lot of loyalty there that you don't... You just try to excel in your job and...
and not try to downgrade somebody else's job.
But there's a lot of competition between wings.
One wing commander and another wing commander.
But he doesn't say that Tex Hetherington is no good.
He just says, I'm better.
And I think this is different probably from civilian life.
But you are, I said all you do is try to excel and I think that probably if you had it do over I would probably develop a little more positive promotion of telling them just like the
going nine months without an accident.
You announce this, you work at it, you accomplish it, and then when you have accomplished it, it's time and we're going to go six months,
Then you invite all the commanders up and say, come on up, and we'll celebrate going six months without an accident.
So you get everybody up there to look at your program, and then you kind of promote yourself that way.
And you think if you would be, I mean, you would have promoted yourself now.
Well, I mean, you would have.
You would have promoted yourself more than you did.
Well, there's a lot of opportunities where you could,
have graphic charts and show as to what a good base you were running and things of this sort.
Whereas you really didn't go out of your way to tell people what a good base you thought you had.
And of course you learn that as you grow up.
from your first command at the 350th Air Division on up.
At that time, I should have promoted them.
But at that time, you didn't get the competition between the bases and various activities to promote enthusiasm and things of this sort.
Well, I think that you're taking over a base by taking over any organization.
And I think this is a problem with even the U.S. government.
We just criticize, criticize, criticize.
And when I went to an in and there base,
or an Air Division and took command of it, why then we just promoted, this is the best, this is the best, this is the best, and you just get everybody believing that you're the best.
And when everybody believes they're the best, then you become the best.
But when you get everybody criticizing and running down, why?
This is a major problem, I think, in running government.
I mean, the president.
Everybody criticized the president.
And instead of promoting the president, I mean, he has a fantastic job to do, and you just can't have all the backbiting, the media and the senators and everybody trying to get ahead.
I don't know what the answer is, but
But you have to develop your enthusiasm.
And we're the best.
And when you do that, why, you become the best.
OK. We're going to talk about leadership this afternoon.
Let's talk about one last thing this morning.
And that is, of course, retirement, substantial change in your life.
What were your thoughts?
about your military career on the day that you retired.
Do you remember?
Well, you really get depressed.
I'll agree.
You really get depressed.
When I retired, my You were still on Hawaii now, right?
No, no.
Or did they fly you back for this?
No, I was shipped back as a patient to Wilfrid Hall.
And the Surgeon General was a friend of mine, so it was just one of those things that he could do.
Although there's nothing wrong with me, I'd taken a physical at Andrews at Washington, and they didn't find anything wrong with me.
So I didn't meet a board, a retirement board, because they didn't think it was necessary.
And then a certain general said, well, he called me up and said, Tex, you would do another physical because you had to move the board.
And they said you didn't need a board.
So where do you would like to get another physical?
And I said, well, I just want to go to Wilford Hall because those people know all about me.
Maybe they'll find something wrong with me.
I can get 10% disability or something, which is a tax break.
And so he said, well, I'll owe you back as a patient.
So he could do that.
So I entered the hospital over there and then he evacuated me back as a patient although we came back to San Francisco and then we picked up a new automobile and drove and so I came back.
